{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"coaching":[{"coaching":"Plan how stale comment update for reclassified signing key will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["fc8242b3709278428"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"stale comment update for reclassified signing key"},{"coaching":"Test the riskiest assumption behind intermediate signing-readiness assumptions in the write seam first.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f8a97711f9eb01f98"],"move_id":"4","move_name":"riskiest-assumption test","subject":"intermediate signing-readiness assumptions in the write seam"}],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":6,"blocking":0,"dropped":8,"indeterminate":0},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","ran":true,"references":0,"resolved":0,"status":"pass"},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":6004,"file_impact":4,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":4,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"fail","verify_commands_linted":59,"verify_lint_abstained":58},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":1523,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":4,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":217.6,"llm_calls":31,"llm_ms":441568.1,"total_ms":441905.3,"verify_requests":18},"remediation":{"baseline":"sidecar","eligible":false,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":false,"plan_changed":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"sidecar_baseline":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","F4","G5","T12","T2","T4","T5b","T5d","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":null,"blocking_enabled":null,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["P6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["vague/subjective terms present: sufficient","verify command `aws ssm start-session … docker exec … env | grep REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY` greps the unanchored word 'REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY' — it substring-matches (e.g. 'review_REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY'); anchor it (\\b, ^$, or a quoted key like '\"REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY\":')"],"finding":"Acceptance-criteria / definition-of-done quality issues.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f607dd457c67f9209","impact":0.4,"is_primary":null,"location":"","norm_id":"ned06ebc801a522e3","priority":0.4,"reason":null,"scenarios":[],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Split compound criteria, replace subjective terms with observable outcomes, and state how each is verified.","tier":"DET","validity":1.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Define the expected type and before/after assertion for `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` in AC2: state whether it is a count, specify that the executor should record its value before driving the review-bot, and add an explicit assertion (e.g. `jq -e '.authorship.signed == BEFORE + 1'`) after the LINK is emitted.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan AC2: 'evidenced by the work ticket's `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` increasing'","No schema definition for `.authorship.signed` anywhere in the plan","No explicit instruction to capture the before-value for this field (only `C` the git SHA is captured before the test)","Verify-command defect taxonomy item 5: missing cardinality assertion when criterion names a count"],"finding":"AC2 requires proving a new LINK event was introduced by asserting that `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` is \"increasing\", but the plan neither defines what `.authorship.signed` returns (a count? a boolean? a list?) nor specifies the before-value to compare against. An executor does not know what numeric or structural value to assert, and if the field returns `null` the comparison is vacuous (taxonomy item 6: prose-vs-structured assertion target with no anchor).","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fe17ea5ebf340e845","impact":0.44,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2(a) — `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` proving sub-check","norm_id":"na1efb10e5ce2b727","priority":0.3422,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["`.authorship.signed` returns null or a boolean on this rebar version; the 'increasing' check is trivially true or crashes","Executor skips this sub-check because they don't know what 'increasing' means for the field type, relying solely on AC2b"],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Replace the prose 'increasing' with a concrete shell snippet: `BEFORE=$(rebar show \"$T\" | jq '.authorship.signed'); # … drive review-bot …; rebar show \"$T\" | jq -e --argjson b \"$BEFORE\" '.authorship.signed == ($b + 1)'` — and clarify in the plan that `.authorship.signed` is the count of cryptographically-signed events on the ticket.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.7778,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify what `.authorship.signed` represents (e.g. 'count of signed events on the ticket') and rephrase the AC2(a) verify step to reference a concrete before/after comparison (e.g. 'count was N before C, confirm it is N+1 or greater after the bot runs').","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed' increasing\" — the field `.authorship.signed` is not defined anywhere in the plan body","The plan body describes signing in terms of the write seam and key presence, not in terms of a ticket-level `.authorship.signed` field","The criterion's stated goal is 'a new LINK event authored by 594c was introduced' — the verify step measures a different, unnamed field"],"finding":"AC2's intermediate verification step references the jq field `.authorship.signed` (described as 'increasing'), but the plan body never defines what this field represents (a count, a boolean, a list?) or how it maps to the stated goal of confirming 'a new LINK event authored by 594c was introduced'. If it is a boolean, 'increasing' is meaningless; if it is a count, the plan should say so. The verify step references an entity not grounded in the plan description, creating a minor E1(b) terminology gap.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4d88e10c53dd6176","impact":0.44,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2(a)","norm_id":"nd0f69ddf7150a777","priority":0.3422,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An implementer runs `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` and receives a boolean `true` — they cannot determine whether 'increasing' is satisfied or what baseline to compare against, stalling the verification step."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Replace `.authorship.signed` with a concrete field description, e.g.: 'confirm `rebar show <work-ticket-id> | jq '.events | map(select(.type==\"LINK\" and .author==\"594c\" and .signed==true)) | length'` is ≥ 1 after the bot runs (and was 0 before `C`)'. This grounds the verify step in the same entities the criterion names (LINK event, author 594c, signed).","tier":"LLM","validity":0.7778,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Tighten the `.authorship.signed` assertion in AC2 to a concrete, operator-executable rule — e.g., capture the pre-event count with `BEFORE=$(rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed')` before driving the review-bot, then assert the post-event count is `> $BEFORE` (and `>= 1`), so the check is unambiguous even when the ticket already has prior signed events.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan AC2: 'evidenced by the work ticket's `rebar show <t> | jq \\'.authorship.signed\\'` increasing, recorded as the work-ticket id + tickets commit (proves non-vacuous)'","`ticket_state.schema.json` has `additionalProperties: true` and does NOT define an `authorship` property — the field's type and semantics are not schema-anchored.","`docs/identity.md:159` defines the field as a count: 'records only presence counts (`authorship: {signed, unsigned}`)' but this is a docs file, not co-located with the AC decision rule.","T8 criterion (b): 'a processing protocol/decision rule referenced but not co-located with the schema that needs it'."],"finding":"AC2's intermediate verification step uses `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` with only the qualifier 'increasing' as the pass/fail rule, but the plan never defines the concrete assertion value an operator must check (e.g., ≥1, or strictly greater than the pre-LINK value). The field `authorship.signed` is a count integer (documented in `docs/identity.md:159` as 'presence counts (`authorship: {signed, unsigned}`)') but is absent from `ticket_state.schema.json`, so the decision rule is not co-located with any schema definition the operator can reference. An executor following AC2 literally cannot know whether 'increasing' means: (a) the value changed from 0 to ≥1, (b) the value is strictly greater than whatever it was before `$C`, or (c) the field simply exists.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff6798c07cb3a01ac","impact":0.44,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, sentence: 'evidenced by the work ticket's `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` increasing'","norm_id":"n95a53fce47190622","priority":0.3422,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["An operator running AC2 sees `.authorship.signed` go from 3 to 4 — is that a pass? The plan says 'increasing' but doesn't say what baseline to compare against or whether any nonzero value suffices.","If the work ticket already had prior signed events before `$C`, the count is already >0 — 'increasing' could be satisfied vacuously by a pre-existing signed event rather than the new LINK event."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Capture the count before the LINK event: `BEFORE=$(git -C .tickets-tracker checkout <work-ticket-branch> && rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed // 0')`. After the bot emits its LINK, assert `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed' > $BEFORE`. This makes 'increasing' precise and non-vacuous even when the ticket has pre-existing signed events.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.7778,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Update (or add as a ticket comment) the stale comment at `fetch-secrets.sh:97` to reflect that the signing key is now security-material for gate compliance (not merely attribution-only), since the plan explicitly reclassifies it — even if no other file changes land, this comment is on the secret-provisioning path and misleads future operators about key criticality.","cohort":["T5c"],"criteria":["T5c"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan 'What' section: 'review-bot reciprocal relates_to LINK on the trailer-cited work ticket → IN-SCOPE WRITER' — explicitly identifying this as gate-enforced","fetch-secrets.sh:97: comment reads 'Blank ⇒ the reviewbot writes unsigned (its types are gate-exempt, so this is attribution only)' — still present, now incorrect per the plan's own classification","Plan Scope: 'No tracked repo-file change (empty file_impact is correct)' — the plan deliberately produces no file change, leaving the stale comment in place","Secret lifecycle boundary: fetch-secrets.sh is the provisioning path for the signing key that the review-bot uses to sign in-scope LINK events"],"finding":"The plan reclassifies the signing key from 'attribution-only/gate-exempt' to security-material (in-scope LINK writes that the merge-gate enforces), but explicitly declines to update the stale comment at fetch-secrets.sh:97 that still describes it as advisory. This leaves operators with a misleading signal about the criticality of populating /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key in SSM.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc8242b3709278428","impact":0.33,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section ('No tracked repo-file change (empty file_impact is correct)') + infra/scripts/fetch-secrets.sh:97","norm_id":"n93304663acb4baa1","priority":0.2063,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A future operator provisioning a new VM reads fetch-secrets.sh:97, concludes the signing key is 'attribution only / gate-exempt', treats the SSM parameter as lower-priority, and deploys without it — the review-bot then silently writes unsigned LINK events that will fail the merge-gate when require_authenticated is enforced (story 8d39).","A security review of fetch-secrets.sh flags the optional treatment of the signing key as appropriate given the comment, missing that it is now security-material for gate compliance."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Change fetch-secrets.sh:97 from \"Blank ⇒ the reviewbot writes unsigned (its types are gate-exempt, so this is attribution only)\" to something like: \"Blank ⇒ the reviewbot writes unsigned. NOTE: the reciprocal relates_to LINK onto non-exempt work tickets (story 1787) IS in-scope for the authorship gate — populating this key is required for gate compliance once require_authenticated enforcement is enabled (story 8d39).\"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.625,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"low","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"medium","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify (or add as a pre-canary check) that the deployed review-bot container has both (a) an active identity pointer resolving to 594c and (b) REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY is picked up by config.load_config as cfg.identity.signing_key — or acknowledge these as what the canary (AC4) is confirming, not pre-conditions already established.","cohort":["E4"],"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'the write seam (_seam.py:294-315) signs when a resolvable author_id (594c, via the bot git email) + a signing_key are present'","_seam.py:180-197: attribution_fields resolves author_id via resolve_current_identity(repo_root), not from email directly — requires the identity pointer to be configured in the deployed tracker","_seam.py:289-294: 'if not require_auth and not signing_key: return' — no signing occurs if config doesn't expose signing_key; whether REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY env var feeds cfg.identity.signing_key is not evidenced in the plan","_seam.py:306: signing failure is caught and logged, event written unsigned — no observable error unless require_authenticated=True"],"finding":"The plan's signing-readiness claim ('the write seam signs when a resolvable author_id (594c, via the bot git email) + a signing_key are present') rests on two intermediate steps that are asserted but not evidenced: (1) that the deployed tracker has an active identity pointer mapping the bot's git email to identity 594c (attribution_fields resolves author_id via resolve_current_identity, not directly from email); and (2) that the REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY env-var path (materialized by fetch-secrets.sh) is correctly picked up by config.load_config into cfg.identity.signing_key. If either is absent or misconfigured, events are written unsigned with no error (the write-gate only raises when require_authenticated=True, which is NOT enabled yet). The plan's 'already provisioned to sign' conclusion could be vacuously true (key on disk, identity pointer absent) while the bot silently writes unsigned — exactly the scenario AC4 warns about.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8a97711f9eb01f98","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What — 'Already provisioned to sign' paragraph / _seam.py:293-315 / fetch-secrets.sh:98-124","norm_id":"nca8004385b6a5e95","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["The bot's identity pointer is not set in the deployed tracker → author_id absent → events written unsigned → AC2/AC4 verify-identity check would catch this, but the plan treats provisioning as proof of signing","REBAR_IDENTITY_SIGNING_KEY path isn't loaded by config.load_config into cfg.identity.signing_key → signing_key is None → silent unsigned writes"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the 'Already provisioned to sign' paragraph, reframe: 'the bot is equipped to sign IF (a) the identity pointer in the deployed tracker resolves to 594c and (b) config.load_config exposes the materialized key path as identity.signing_key — both confirmed by the canary (AC4) rather than by provisioning alone.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.6667,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify and record the exact CLI flag that scopes `rebar verify-identity` to a starting commit boundary (run `rebar verify-identity --help` on the deployed VM and confirm `--since` is the accepted spelling), or replace `--since \"$C\"` with the correct flag in AC2.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan AC2: 'rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"' exits 0","Verify-command defect taxonomy item 3: wrong helper-script argv — cross-check flag names against --help","No reference in the plan to the rebar CLI's accepted flag spelling for this boundary argument"],"finding":"The `rebar verify-identity` proving command uses `--since \"$C\"` (where `$C` is a git SHA), but the plan does not cross-reference the actual CLI flag name. If the flag is named differently (e.g., `--after`, `--from-commit`, `--from`) the command will either error out or — worse — silently ignore the unrecognized flag and verify ALL historical events, producing a false-green exit-0 that does not scope to post-`C` events and does not prove the new LINK was signed.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fde5fad782cb7dc3c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2 — `rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"` proving command","norm_id":"n6be2ed187e6509c3","priority":0.0,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["An executor runs the command with a misspelled flag; rebar ignores it and exits 0 against the full event log, masking an unsigned LINK event","A future rebar CLI refactor renames the flag; the AC continues to pass vacuously"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a prerequisite step: `rebar verify-identity --help | grep -- '--since'` — if the flag is absent, use whichever boundary flag appears (e.g. `--from-commit`). Update the AC to use the confirmed spelling, e.g. `rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --from-commit \"$C\"`","tier":"LLM","validity":0.25,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"no","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Identify whether the prior 'review-bot is fully gate-exempt' assessment was recorded in any ADR, design doc, or canonical reference, and if so add a task to update it (or note 'no external doc exists' to close the question).","cohort":["T2","T4","T7"],"criteria":["T7"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states: 'This LINK-write path refines the earlier \"review-bot writes only the exempt code_review type\" assessment — the reciprocal relates_to back-link onto the non-exempt work ticket was not accounted for there'","The plan records corrected classification only as ticket comments: 'the classification + canary evidence are recorded as comments on this ticket'","No mention of updating any ADR, design doc, or prior story that may have stated the bot was fully gate-exempt"],"finding":"The plan explicitly acknowledges that the prior assessment — 'review-bot writes only the exempt code_review type' — was incorrect and is now refined. If that prior assessment was recorded in any ADR, design doc, or story artifact (plausible given it warranted a correction note here), those documents are now stale. The plan only records the corrected classification as ticket comments and does not call out whether any existing doc/ADR needs updating.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc7334c88ed88b52c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"## What — enumerate and classify every Gerrit-side store operation (final bullet: 'refines the earlier…assessment')","norm_id":"nc7b2038c0e25a618","priority":0.0,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["A future engineer reads an ADR or doc that still says 'review-bot is fully gate-exempt' and incorrectly relies on that for a new service design or enforcement decision","The stale doc is found during an audit and creates confusion about the authoritative classification"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a sentence such as: 'Prior assessment recorded in [doc/ADR/story X] — update that reference to reflect the corrected classification (reciprocal relates_to LINK on non-exempt work tickets is in-scope and signed).' If no external doc exists, state that explicitly to close the question.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.4286,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"insufficient","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"na","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Reconcile the reconciler's scope assignment: either update dc09 story 3's description to remove 'reconciler' from the Gerrit-side mandate (because it is truly GitHub-side only, as the leaf argues) before this leaf is finalized, or add a classification entry in this leaf confirming the reconciler has no Gerrit-side write path (with file/line evidence matching the level of detail given for opcert-service and the review-bot).","cohort":["G7"],"criteria":["G7"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["dc09 story 3 text: 'confirm the deployed review-bot / reconciler / opcert-service signs its ticket writes on the VM'","Leaf exclusion: 'the Jira→rebar reconciler is a GitHub-side writer — reconcile-bridge.yml, runs-on: ubuntu-latest — covered by story 4dc0, NOT Gerrit-side'","The leaf's scope section states 'Gerrit-side operations only: classification + verification' but does not acknowledge the discrepancy with the parent's enumeration of reconciler under story 3","Per the CONFLICT RULE, the parent wins: if the reconciler truly belongs to the GitHub-side story (4dc0), the parent's story 3 description must be updated first"],"finding":"The leaf excludes the Gerrit-side reconciler from its scope and delegates it to GitHub-side story 4dc0, but the parent (dc09) story 3 description explicitly names 'reconciler' alongside 'review-bot' and 'opcert-service' as a Gerrit-side service to confirm. This is a scope redefinition against the parent's text, not a consistent narrowing.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f50145516fd1437fe","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Leaf 'What — enumerate and classify every Gerrit-side store operation' section; specifically the parenthetical '(For contrast: the Jira→rebar reconciler is a GitHub-side writer — reconcile-bridge.yml, runs-on: ubuntu-latest — covered by story 4dc0, NOT Gerrit-side.)' vs. dc09 Scope/planned child stories item 3: 'confirm the deployed review-bot / reconciler / opcert-service signs its ticket writes on the VM'","norm_id":"n8f21a5ef383db3b7","priority":0.0,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["The reconciler's Gerrit-side signing status is never confirmed by this leaf (it's excluded), and if 4dc0 doesn't cover it either, there's a coverage gap before the enforcement flip (8d39).","During the 8d39 enforcement flip's AC review, 'Gerrit-side' coverage may be assessed against dc09's story 3 text — which still names the reconciler — causing confusion or an unverified gap."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a classification entry in the leaf's 'What' table: '**reconcile-bridge → GITHUB-SIDE ONLY, NON-GERRIT.** Runs on `runs-on: ubuntu-latest` (`.github/workflows/reconcile-bridge.yml`), never on the Gerrit VM; all its ticket writes originate from GitHub Actions runners. Confirmed by story 4dc0; zero Gerrit-VM write paths exist.' Then update dc09's story 3 description to read '…confirm the deployed review-bot / opcert-service signs its ticket writes on the VM (reconciler is GitHub-side, covered by story 4dc0)' so the parent and leaf are consistent.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.375,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"module","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The AC2 (and AC4) proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` contains a structural defect: `--arg u E` passes the *literal string* \"E\" as jq's `$u` variable (jq's `--arg name value` syntax), not the shell variable expansion of `E`. An operator copying this verbatim will always get exit 0 — the filter trivially passes because no real event uuid equals the literal character 'E' — producing a false-green verification regardless of whether the LINK event actually appears in the non-verified report.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3b0873b9f1f93b17","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2 proving command: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`; also repeated in AC4 operator-attested block","norm_id":"n6fcc7a16314d1301","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace the bare `E` in the jq call with a quoted shell expansion. Full corrected sequence for AC2:\n```sh\nE=<uuid recorded from the LINK event above>\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json \\\n  | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nThe double-quoted `\"$E\"` causes the shell to expand the variable before passing its value to jq as the `--arg` literal.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"no","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"no","respects_artifact_altitude":"na","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The AC2 (and AC4) proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` is mechanically broken at the CLI flag level: jq's `--arg name value` syntax assigns the *literal token* `value` to jq variable `$name`, so `--arg u E` sets `$u = \"E\"` (the four-character string), not the shell variable `$E` holding the recorded event uuid. As written, the command compares every event_uuid to the literal string 'E', exits 0 trivially, and provides no actual verification — the signed LINK event could appear in the non-verified report undetected.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f9085068f07d49b63","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2 proving command; AC4 (operator-attested) proving command","norm_id":"n3491250729a44615","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` with `jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` in both AC2 and AC4, and make explicit that `E` is a shell variable (e.g., `E=<recorded-uuid>`) set before running the command.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"no","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"no","respects_artifact_altitude":"na","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` passes the literal four-character string \"E\" to jq — not the shell variable holding the actual event uuid — because `--arg u E` is a positional argument, not a shell expansion. An operator copying the command verbatim will silently test for the absence of the literal string \"E\" from the report, which always passes, producing a false-green result.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f56a6d5c764487a77","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2 proving command: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n9ac527a94a3c08f8","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add before the command: `export E=<uuid recorded above>`, then:\n```\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json \\\n  | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nThe double-quoted `\"$E\"` ensures the shell expands the variable before passing it to jq.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"no","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"no","respects_artifact_altitude":"na","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The first half of AC2's proving command (`rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'`) checks an aggregate field on the work ticket, not the specific LINK event written by the review-bot. If the work ticket already has one or more signed events from other authors, this check passes even if the bot's reciprocal LINK event is unsigned, giving a false-green result for the criterion 'signature present on the LINK-target ticket'.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fd2129d957af1e94c","impact":0.55,"is_primary":null,"location":"AC2: `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'`","norm_id":"n42561480543d135e","priority":0.2444,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":[],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Replace:\n```\nrebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'\n```\nWith (after `export E=<uuid>`):\n```\nrebar show <t> | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e '.events[] | select(.uuid == $u) | .signed == true'\n```\nThis isolates the signature assertion to the bot's specific LINK event.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.4444,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"yes","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"AC2's first proving command (`rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'`) checks a ticket-level aggregate signed count, not the specific LINK event. If the work ticket already has any other signed event (e.g., a signed creation event predating this story), the command exits 0 even if the new LINK event is unsigned — a fixture-invalidity false positive that AC2's second command (uuid-specific absence from the non-verified report) is meant to catch but that makes the first command misleading as standalone evidence of 'the LINK event is signed'.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f37717daa9f05a4ea","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, proving command 1: `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'`","norm_id":"n7bf86331ae5547ff","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace the aggregate check with an event-specific assertion, e.g.:\n```\nrebar show <t> --events | jq -e --arg u \"$E\" 'any(.[]; .uuid == $u and (.signature // \"\") != \"\")'\n```\nor simply remove the first command and document that the second command (`all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)` against the non-verified report) is the sole definitive gate, since it is already event-uuid-specific.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.375,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"no","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"901cc01f15f1e36a","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":217.6,"llm_calls":31,"llm_ms":441568.1,"total_ms":441905.3,"verify_requests":18},"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","regver":"b293b9a55de591cc","runner":"pydantic_ai","schema":"plan_review_result_v2","ticket_id":"1a51-b170-5168-46d2","ticket_type":"story","verdict":"PASS","verified_at_sha":"6b25dbead186639a436b1d5faf7cb03e99001efc"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"REVIEW_RESULT","timestamp":1784239251421884001,"uuid":"e91b6446-921c-4400-8d74-ce6f13feb73b"}